&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;
<ol>
 	<li><strong><u>Your Contact Information</u></strong>– This information should be IDENTICAL to what is on your resume header.</li>
</ol>
Name
Address
City, State, Zip Code
Phone Number
Email Address

Date- use the full month name (example: October 17, 2013)
<ol start="2">
 	<li><strong><u>Employer Contact Information </u></strong></li>
</ol>
Name of person you are writing to
Title
Company
Address
City, State, Zip Code

What happens if you don’t know the name of the hiring manager from the job advertisement? There are several options.
<ul>
 	<li>Check online to see if the name of a hiring manager is available</li>
 	<li>You can CALL the company and ask if no name is on their website</li>
</ul>
<em>How would you ask this of a staff member at the company?</em>
<ul>
 	<li>You can simply put “Hiring Manager” or whatever title the job advertisement suggests.</li>
</ul>
<ol start="3">
 	<li><strong><u>Salutation</u></strong>
Dear Mr./Ms. Last Name</li>
</ol>
Note: It is NEVER okay to use “Mrs.” UNLESS the job advertisement directs you to do so. This is an out-of-date greeting.


________________________________________________________________________________
<strong>The Cover Letter Body</strong>

<em>This is where most of the text of your cover letter is written. It’s as simple as three paragraphs. </em>
<ol>
 	<li><strong><u>First Paragraph</u></strong></li>
</ol>
The first paragraph of your letter tells <strong>why</strong> you are writing.  You should be sure to:
<ul>
 	<li>Say what position you are applying for</li>
 	<li>WHERE you saw the job ad</li>
 	<li>WHEN you found the advertisement (e.g., <em>Metro</em> newspaper on Sept. 1)</li>
</ul>
Also, if you have been referred to the position by someone in your NETWORK, be sure to use this person’s name in this paragraph.
<ol start="2">
 	<li><strong><u>Second Paragraph</u></strong></li>
</ol>
This paragraph is the one that you use to really show what a great fit you are for the job!
<ul>
 	<li>Highlight achievements, jobs, and skills taken from your resume.
<ul>
 	<li>Make sure to pick the examples most relevant to the job.</li>
 	<li>You don’t have to talk about every item on your resume!</li>
</ul>
</li>
 	<li>Use positive ACTION WORDS and TRANSFERRABLE SKILLS that tell the employer how you will benefit them and why you are the best fit.</li>
 	<li>Do not repeat your resume word-for-word.</li>
</ul>
This could end up being two or more paragraphs as you gain more experience!
<ol start="3">
 	<li><strong><u>Third Paragraph </u></strong></li>
</ol>
There are THREE parts to the final paragraph.
<ul>
 	<li><strong>First</strong>, you must THANK the employer for considering you for the position and/or for taking the time to read your cover letter and resume.</li>
 	<li><strong>Second</strong>, be sure to ASK FOR WHAT YOU WANT (an interview) and express your enthusiastic interest in the position.</li>
 	<li><strong>Third</strong>, let the employer know you will be FOLLOWING UP with them in <em>specific period</em> of time.</li>
</ul>
<ol start="4">
 	<li><strong><u>Closing</u></strong></li>
</ol>
<ul>
 	<li>Be sure to use professional language such as ”Sincerely” or “Regards.”</li>
 	<li>Type your name a space or two below.</li>
 	<li>If you are sending a hard copy (or a PDF of a printed letter) be sure to SIGN the letter in the space between the closing language and your printed name.
<ul>
 	<li>If you are emailing the letter, it’s okay to just type your name.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-44305" src="http://p2i.pyd.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/job-ad-cover-letters-2-3a.png" alt="job-ad-cover-letters-2-3a" width="706" height="308" />

